Yes, pneumonia detection from X-rays is a good project idea for your resume, especially for a Data Science/ML profile.

It works well because it shows:

Computer vision skills
Medical-image workflow understanding
End-to-end ML pipeline ability
Real-world impact thinking
Use it, but do it in a way that looks professional and realistic.

How To Start

Define a clear goal: “Classify chest X-rays into normal vs pneumonia.”
Pick a public dataset: start with Kaggle Chest X-ray Pneumonia dataset, then mention limits.
Build a baseline first: simple CNN or transfer learning with ResNet/EfficientNet.  //i think using transformers are better than cnn as cnn ab outdated ho gye
Evaluate properly: accuracy is not enough; include precision, recall, F1, ROC-AUC, and confusion matrix.
Handle data issues: class imbalance, train/val/test split, augmentation, leakage checks.
Add explainability: Grad-CAM or similar so you can show what the model focused on.
Write a strong report: problem, data, preprocessing, model, metrics, errors, limitations, future work.
Deploy a small demo: Streamlit app is enough for portfolio.

What Recruiters Will Like Most

Reproducibility: clean GitHub repo, requirements, instructions to run.
Business/clinical framing: false negatives vs false positives tradeoff.
Honest limitations: “not for clinical use,” dataset bias, label quality concerns.
Comparison: baseline vs improved model with clear metric gains.
Important
Medical AI is sensitive. Avoid claiming “diagnostic tool.” Frame it as a learning/research project and emphasize ethical limits.

